Here are the correct answers to your CA170 multiple-choice questions:

What is this script doing? grep string file > /dev/null \n if test "$?" = "0"

    Testing whether or not the string occurs in the file, without listing the lines on which it does.
    (It discards the output to /dev/null and then checks the exit status $? of the grep command to see if a match was found).

In my Shakespeare directory, you want to count on how many lines the string "King" appears in Shakespeare. Which of the following will answer that question?

    grep King */act* | wc -l

One of the following file protections will break your web page:

    -rwxr-x--x
    (The web server runs as a different user ("others/world") and requires read permission to serve the file. The --x at the end means it can execute but cannot read it).

Which of the following fails to find lines containing "Scotland" in a group of files?

    grep scotland *html
    (Because grep is case-sensitive by default).

As a result of the "unused RAM is wasted RAM" idea, we may:

    Keep data from terminated processes in memory. And pre-load processes that may be run later.
    (Modern OSes use unused memory as a cache to speed up the system).

This shell conditional: if test "$1" = "1" is true if:

    The first argument is the string "1".
    ($1 refers to the first positional argument passed to the script).

This character should be avoided in Unix filenames:

    * (star)

This command: sed -e 's|<|\&lt;|g'

    is displaying the start of HTML tags but not getting them interpreted.

On Linux, when you type a normal command, it should be in the PATH to run. Yet when you run ps -f you see a program running that is not in the PATH. How can this happen?

    You can run programs that are not in the PATH.
    (By providing the absolute or relative path directly, e.g., ./my_script.sh or /opt/bin/program).

Swapping a process or part of a process to disk works with:

    Run-time binding only.
    (Because when the process is swapped back into memory, it will likely be put in a different physical location than before).

With compile-time binding, the memory locations used can be changed if the program is re-compiled. Why does the OS not do this?

    The source code may not be available.

In a modern OS, one of these is false:

    My running program is normally saved to disk when I shut down.
    (RAM is volatile; running state is wiped on standard shutdown, not saved to the disk).

I am in the directory /stuff/and/things and I type: cd ../../../more/things - What directory am I in now?

    /more/things

You write a simple program in assembly language (or "machine code", or "native instructions"). You then want to run the program on a different type of machine (different chip). Which is normally true:

    The program must be re-written.
    (Assembly/machine code is architecture-specific. Code for an Intel chip will not run natively on an ARM chip).

I am in the directory /stuff/and/things and I type: cd more/things - What directory am I in now?

    /stuff/and/things/more/things
    (Because there is no leading slash, it acts as a relative path moving deeper into the current directory).

Linux dominates supercomputers and other specialist computer niches because:

    Open source Linux can be customised to unusual hardware.

One of these is true.

    A command-line system is easier to automate than a GUI system.

This program: function f() { f(); } f();

    Runs time-sliced until it crashes by running out of stack space.
    (This is an infinite recursion that will cause a Stack Overflow).

The relationship of Paging to Swapping is:

    Disk is used as a slow-speed overflow of memory, so that the system slows down gracefully rather than suddenly.

The commands "cd" followed by "cd public_html" followed by "mkdir ../stuff" make a directory called:

    $HOME/stuff

We are searching for text in chapters of a book, called names like chap17.html. One of these is definitely not right:

    grep Scotland \*chap*html
    (The backslash escapes the first star, making it literally look for a file whose name starts with an asterisk character).

A program is a stream of instructions to be executed. When an OS runs a program, it starts the CPU executing that stream of instructions. How does the OS ever get control of the machine back?

    The program will receive periodic timer interrupts.
    (Hardware interrupts force the CPU to return control to the OS scheduler).

What will this Shell script do? for i in * \n do \n rm i \n done

    Remove a file called i, perhaps multiple times.
    (Because the script says rm i instead of rm $i, it literally targets a file named "i" instead of the variable's value).

When we run multiple programs at the same time, we need:

    Memory protection.

On a multi-user system, when one user's program divides by zero:

    An interrupt is generated and the program is terminated.
